We recommended that the City Accountant: 

Make representation with LBP, Sagay Branch regarding the date of availability of the monthly bank statement. In case, the monthly bank statement is not available after five days from end of the month, immediately request for snapshots of the bank transactions for the month; 

Promptly prepare the monthly BRS for all current accounts of the City; 

Avail of the online service facilities of LBP to obtain real time monthly bank statements;

Draw journal voucher for valid book reconciling items that require correction or adjustment in the GL; and

Inform the bank in case there are bank reconciling items for adjustment by the bank right after the BRS is issued.

We recommended that:

The City Accountant and the City Treasurer take up collections from sale of bid documents and other sources as trust receipts in the Trust Fund Books pursuant to DBM BC No. 2004-5A and prepare adjusting entry to reclassify the balance of proceeds from sale of bid documents recorded under the Due from Officers and Employees to Surplus; 

The BAC Chairs/Members and Secretariat refund the amount of ₱626,874.50 representing honoraria claimed during months of March-April 2019 and May-June 2019, in the amount of ₱313,324.00 and ₱313,550.50, respectively since payments was not covered by Appropriation Ordinance;

The City Budget Officer and the City Accountant Officer strictly observe Item 3.1.4 of DBM Budget Circular No. 2007-3, in case the City’s savings is utilized in the payment of honoraria of BAC Chairs and Members and the TWG; and

Any excess of the amount collected after paying all obligations on honoraria shall form part of the local government funds pursuant to Item 6.2 of Budget Circular No. 2004-5A dated October 7, 2005.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

Require the City’s Solid Waste Management Board to prepare/update its 10-year SWM Plan pursuant to national framework and in accordance with the requirements of RA No. 9003; 

Direct the Punong Barangays to establish MRF in their respective barangays which will serve as the receiver of mixed wastes for final sorting, segregation, composting, and recycling;

Support financially the barangays which have no funds to establish the MRFs; and

Direct the Head of CENRO to assign garbage compactor to regularly collect residual solid wastes from urban and rural barangays of the City except those situated in the mountainous areas to be properly dumped at the Sanitary Land Fill.

We recommended that: 

The City Mayor follow up with the Office of the Ombudsman-Visayas, the status of the Evaluation Report submitted by COA Regional Satellite Audit Office-NIS, Bacolod City. 

The City Treasurer tightly implement  Internal Control procedures concerning the overall treasury operations in her office;

The City Treasurer expedite the enhancement of  RPTAR computer system by including in the system a built-in security measures to prevent manipulation in the database;

The City Treasurer establish an effective mechanisms to strictly monitor the correct payment of every taxpayer for RPT and other taxes as shown in the original OR versus the amount reflected in the duplicate and triplicate copies of the same OR as well as intact deposit of collections and ensure correct recording of collections in the books; 

A separate accountable officer be assigned in the assessment, collection, deposit and recording function and a possible rotation in work assignments; and

The City Accountant regularly monitor actual collections for RPT versus RPT Receivable booked up in the books for General and Special Education Funds and immediately inform the City Treasurer in case of low collection efficiency.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the City Treasurer and Economic Enterprise Management Officer to:  

Implement surcharge and penalties on delinquent market stall/block/space holders and strictly impose sanctions thereof pursuant to the provisions embodied under the City’s 2013 Revised Revenue Code;

Stipulation for surcharge  and penalties be provided in the Contract of Lease;

Maintain a complete and updated record on the Inventory of the City’s Market block/stall/space by area to facilitate monitoring of collections and delinquencies; 

Exert joint effort to maximize collections from Market operations as one of the City’s revenue generating programs for the attainment of additional income to finance various programs, activities, and projects beneficial to the constituents.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

11.a Assign personnel who will gather all documents relative to the construction of the AEMSMDH particularly contracts and its supporting documents for every phase of the project including plans and drawings and submit the same to the Auditor pursuant to the requirements of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009;

11.b Expedite the completion of the AEMSMDH which has been constructed since CY 2010 to ensure optimum utilization of the fund so that the services and benefits from these projects are delivered to the constituents; 

11.c Direct the City Engineer to exercise close supervision on the construction of AEMSMDH to ensure that actual work of the constructor is in accordance with plans and specifications; and

11.d Direct the City Accountant to prepare a reliable SL for the project, indicating details of contract cost for every phase of the project, the source of fund for every phase of the project and the total cost incurred for the project as of current date.

We recommended that:
a)	The City Mayor submit documents as proof that the City has generated monetary savings as a result of the suggestions, inventions, superior accomplishments and other personal efforts of the employees or group of employees as basis for the grant of monetary awards using the Sagay City PRAISE as authority;

b)	PRAISE Committee submit evaluation reports or any documentation recognizing the productivity, creativeness made or ethical behavior of employees or group of employees making them eligible for the PRAISE monetary awards and incentives;

c)	The Accountant ensure that the amount of incentives  granted shall not exceed 20% of the monetary savings generated from inventions, suggestions and superior accomplishments pursuant to the policies of the CSC PRAISE; and 

d.)	submit specific legal basis for the grant of Achievement Incentives in the event that it could not submit aforementioned requirements.   Otherwise, the said incentives be refunded by the City government officials and employees for lack of specific legal authority.

We recommended that the City Mayor: 

Instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical inventory count annually of the City’s PPEs including the non-movable PPE items, reconcile the result of physical count with accounting records and recommend adjustment for any noted discrepancy pursuant to Section 124 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I; 

Require the City Accountant and the GSO to identify PPE items included in their records with no details or descriptions and disclose the amount in the Notes to the Financial Statement and in the RPCPPE so that the users of the reports are informed of the real discrepancies in the PPE accounts;

Require the GSO and the City Accounting Office to record properly the properties acquired with complete descriptions in the PPE ledger cards and in the property cards, respectively; and

Direct the City General Services Officer to maintain and regularly update property cards of all PPEs, in addition to AREs/PARs already maintained pursuant to Section 119 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume 1.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

Require employees accountable for properties issued to them, which have become unserviceable or no longer needed to return the same to the Head of the Department or Office; 

Instruct the Head of the Department or Office to turn over or return all unserviceable properties, if no longer needed by his office, to the GSO pursuant to Section 167, Rule 22 of COA Circular No. 92-386;

Direct the GSO to immediately prepare a consolidated IIRUP and submit an application for disposal of all unserviceable properties with the COA Audit Team following the procedures provided under Section 167, Rule 22 of COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992; and

Direct the City Accountant to record the disposal of the unserviceable properties in the books after their disposal pursuant to Rule 29, Title V of the Rules and Regulations on Supply and Property Management prescribed under COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992.

